      '</span>\t\u201cEmpathy acts like a spotlight, focusing one\'s attention on a single individual in the here and now. This can have positive effects, but it&nbsp;<span style="font-family: ;">can</span><span style="font-family: ;"> also lead to short-sighted and unfair moral actions.\u201d This idea is paraphrased in option 1. Therefore, option [4] is incorrect. Refer paragraph 4: \u201cFor those in the helping professions, compassion and understanding are critically important. But not empathy\u2026\u201d Thus, option [3] contradicts the passage in saying that empathy is a vital part of helping professions. The word \u2018involuntary\u2019 invalidates option [2]\u2014empathy is only one of the many alternatives to being a good person. As long as we can choose not to empathize with someone, it\u2019s a voluntary emotion. Refer paragraph 2: \u201cAnd it is subject to bias \u2014 both laboratory studies and anecdotal experiences show that empathy flows most for those who look like us, who are attractive and who are non-threatening and familiar.\u201d Therefore, option [1] is true in what it says about empathy.&nbsp;</span><span style="font-family: ;">Hence, [1].</span>',
