      "<p><strong>The</strong><strong> passage given below is followed by four summaries. Choose the option that best captures the author\u2019s position.</strong><br /><br /><br />As a view within political philosophy, egalitarianism has to do both with how people are treated and with distributive justice. Civil rights movements reject certain types of social and political discrimination and demand that people be treated equally. Distributive justice is another form of egalitarianism that addresses life outcomes and the allocation of valuable things such as income, wealth, and other goods. Is egalitarianism about subjective feelings of well-being, about wealth and income, about a broader conception of resources, or some other alternative? This leads us to the question of whether an equal distribution of the preferred metric deals with the starting gate of each person\u2019s life or with equality of life outcomes.</p>",
