    Items:
      '<p>If in the following equation x and y are integers, then how many sets of solutions do the equation have?</p>\n<p><img src="https://imsclick2cert.blob.core.windows.net/imsitemimages/636953342972069384_4427000.JPG" alt="" width="321" height="30" /></p>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\u00a0</p>\n<p><em>Enter your response (as an integer) using the virtual keyboard in the box provided\u00a0</em></p>\n<p><em><br /></em></p>\n<p><em>[quizky-text]</em></p>',
    ItemPassageID: 0,
    PassageItemIndex: 0,
    Passage: null,
    PassageTitle: null,
    IsLinkedQuestion: null,
    Points: 3,
    NegativePoints: 0,
    Explanation:
      '<p>The equation can be reduced to (y + 13)(y \u2013 13) = (x + 17)(x \u2013 17)</p>\n<p><img src="https://imsclick2cert.blob.core.windows.net/imsitemimages/636900824476105050_3511935.PNG" alt="" width="21" height="19" />\u00a0x<sup>2</sup> \u2013 y<sup>2</sup> = 120</p>\n<p>i.e., (x + y)(x \u2013 y) = 2 \u00d7 2 \u00d7 2 \u00d7 3 \u00d7 5</p>\n<p>Taking (x \u2013 y) = 2;</p>\n<p>(x + y) = 2 \u00d7 2 \u00d7 3 \u00d7 5 = 60</p>\n<p>This gives x = 31 and y = 29.</p>\n<p>Taking (x \u2013 y) = 4; (x + y) = 30</p>\n<p>This gives x = 17 and y = 13.</p>\n<p>If x \u2013 y = 6, x + y = 20. This gives x = 13, y = 7 and if x \u2013 y = 10, x + y = 12. This gives x = 11, y = 1. \u00a0\u00a0</p>\n<p>We cannot have x \u2013 y = 5 or 8.</p>\n<p>But for the given equation to hold true we cannot have y \u2264 13 and x \u2264 17.</p>\n<p>This implies x = 31 and\u00a0 y = 29 is the only solution.</p>\n<p>Therefore, the required answer is 1.</p>',
